author: hamaguchi
title: Deep Levels Associated with Molybdenum in Silicon
comments: DLTS peak at 170K. Resistivity 10 Ohm.cm. For FZ Mo was spun on, and thermally diffused. For CZ it was introduced into the melt. Both dopants were used for CZ and FZ. Found 3 other levels related to Mo; Ev+0.27, Ec-0.34, Ec-0.58 and not Mo and dopant pairing.

author: pettersson
title: Electrical and optical properties of molybdenum and tungsten related defects in silicon
comments: DLTS peak at 180K. Capture cross section measured of 50 deg from 150 to 200 deg. Claims not a substitutional site. In a similar publication showing the same data a year later. DOI;10.1557/PROC-262-489. On Zhou's result of extra energy levels they say "Although, in principle, this level could originate from three different defects we think there are good reasons to believe that the midgap level is a kind of process induced built-in defect which has to be studied further before a correct chemical identification can be performed."

author: mullins
title: Thermally activated defects in float zone silicon: Effect of nitrogen on the introduction of deep level states
comments: This is in reference to a defect in FZ silicon for thermal treatments between 400-800 degrees. Comments on complex nature of defects and assignment to chemical nature. Indicates this is likley to be related to Nitrogen and Vacancies. This is as in Nitrogen lean samples the defect does not appear in DLTS, and when Nickle is introduced into the samples it takes a substitutionary  (destroying a vacancy) and leads to lower amount of defects detected by DLTS.

author: vaqueiro
title: Identification of the mechanism responsible for the boron oxygen light induced degradation in silicon photovoltaic cells
comments: This is the precursor one state of the the "BO" defect. The chemical assignment was not measured but inferred. Negative U defect. Capture rates measured, but parameterization not provided. Capture rates depended on Doping in an unusual manner, i.e. was higher for light doping.
